[size=16pt][b]Why Post-Quantum Matters NOW[/b][/size]

Quantum computers are advancing rapidly. NIST finalized post-quantum cryptography standards (FIPS 203/204) in 2024 because the threat is real. The "harvest now, decrypt later" attack means adversaries are already collecting encrypted data and blockchain transactions to break later when quantum computers are powerful enough.

Most cryptocurrencies use ECDSA or Schnorr signatures that a sufficiently powerful quantum computer could break using Shor's algorithm. Retrofitting quantum resistance into existing chains is extremely difficult -- it requires hard forks, new address formats, and migration periods.

Dilithion uses CRYSTALS-Dilithium3 from genesis block zero. No migration needed. No quantum hard fork to wait for. Your coins are protected from day one.

